Fix the error

It looks like the error is caused by trying to redefine `socketManagerService` when its property descriptor is non-configurable. To fix this error, you can make the property descriptor configurable while creating it.

Here's how you can do this, inside the `beforeEach` block:

```typescript
beforeEach(async () => {
    sandbox = createSandbox();
    gameStorageServiceStub = createStubInstance(GameStorageService);
    socketManagerServiceStub = createStubInstance(SocketManager);

    const app = Container.get(Application);
    Object.defineProperty(app['gamesController'], 'gameStorageService', { 
        value: gameStorageServiceStub,
        configurable: true // add this line
    });
    Object.defineProperty(app['gamesController'], 'socketManagerService', {
        value: socketManagerServiceStub,
        configurable: true // add this line
    });
    expressApp = app.app;
});
```

By adding `configurable: true`, you are allowing the `gameStorageService` and `socketManagerService` properties to be redefined later, avoiding the `TypeError` you encountered.

To disable PWA in Quasar, you can follow the steps below:

1. Open the "quasar.conf.js" file in your Quasar project directory.
2. Find the "build" property in the configuration object and scroll down to the "pwa" property.
3. Set the "pwa" property to "false".
4. Save the file.

Here's an example of what the "build" property should look like:

```
module.exports = function (ctx) {
  return {
    // ...
    build: {
      // ...
      pwa: false,
      // ...
    },
    // ...
  }
}
```

Once you have disabled PWA, the service worker and caching should no longer be active, and your website should no longer reload automatically.

If you are only using the `quasar dev` command to run your Quasar app without building it yet, then you can disable the PWA plugin by commenting out the following code in your `src/main.js` file:

```
import { register } from 'register-service-worker'

if (process.env.PROD) {
  register(`${process.env.BASE_URL}service-worker.js`, {
    ready () {
      console.log('App is being served from cache by a service worker.\n' +
        'For more details, visit https://goo.gl/AFskqB')
    },
    registered () {
      console.log('Service worker has been registered.')
    },
    cached () {
      console.log('Content has been cached for offline use.')
    },
    updatefound () {
      console.log('New content is downloading.')
    },
    updated () {
      console.log('New content is available; please refresh.')
    },
    offline () {
      console.log('No internet connection found. App is running in offline mode.')
    },
    error (error) {
      console.error('Error during service worker registration:', error)
    }
  })
}
```

By commenting out this code, you are preventing the PWA plugin from registering a service worker and caching your resources, which should stop your app from reloading automatically every two seconds.

