The Lorenz attractor is a system of first-order ordinary differential equations that was originally developed to model convection currents in the atmosphere. In it simplified form, the Lorenx equations can be written as: dx/dt=alpha*(y-x), dy.dt=x(rho-z)-y, dz/dt=xy-beta*z where x,y and z are three quantities of interest, t denotes time and the constant alpha, rho, and beta are system parameters related to the physical system. The lorenz system is famous for having a chaotic behavior for certain choices of initial conditions and parameters. You are required to solve the lorenz system using the built in ode solve "ode45". The function should have the following inputs: "tSpan": the starting and ending time of the solution , [t0,tf]. "S0": vector containing the initial conditions of the sytstem at t=t0. It contains the initial state of each variable; S0=[x0,y0,z0]. "sigma", "rho", and "mcode": system parameters (constans). The popular term Butterfly effect in chaos theory stems from the solution of a lorentz system and decribes the sensitivity of a system to the choice of initial conditions. FOr a very small change in the initial conditions or the system parameters can result in a big difference in the solution, hence it is a chaotic system. Below is the solution of the Lorentz system in teh time interval tSPan=[0 100] with the system parameters sigma=10, beta=8/3 and rho=28 and the initial conditions S0=[1,1,1]. you can generate a similar visualization using "plot3" function of matlab. Tips you have to use: Read the documentation of "ode45". The first argument of "ode45" is a function handle. Carefully define this to describe the lorenz system. The default settings of "ode45" should be sufficient to solve this system. Generating the above plot is not required. You are given the following code in matlab just fill it : 
function [T, X, Y, Z] = lorenzSolver(tSpan, S0, sigma, rho, beta)
 
 
 
end

function [T, X, Y, Z] = lorenzSolver(tSpan, S0, sigma, rho, beta)
    % Define the Lorenz system as a function of state and time
    lorenzSys = @(t, S) [sigma * (S(2) - S(1));  % dx/dt
                         S(1) * (rho - S(3)) - S(2);  % dy/dt
                         S(1) * S(2) - beta * S(3)];  % dz/dt

    % Solve the system of ODEs using ode45
