A priority queue with nodes can be implemented in Java using a Binary Heap (Min-Heap or Max-Heap). Here's a simple example of a Min-Heap priority queue with nodes in Java:

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

class Node {
    int key;
    String value;

    public Node(int key, String value) {
        this.key = key;
        this.value = value;
    }
}

public class PriorityQueue {
    private List<Node> heap;

    public PriorityQueue() {
        heap = new ArrayList<>();
    }

    private int parent(int i) {
        return (i - 1) / 2;
    }

    private int left(int i) {
        return 2 * i + 1;
    }

    private int right(int i) {
        return 2 * i + 2;
    }

    private boolean hasParent(int i) {
        return i > 0;
    }

    private boolean hasLeft(int i) {
        return left(i) < heap.size();
    }

    private boolean hasRight(int i) {
        return right(i) < heap.size();
    }

    private void swap(int i, int j) {
        Node temp = heap.get(i);
        heap.set(i, heap.get(j));
        heap.set(j, temp);
    }

    public void offer(int key, String value) {
        Node node = new Node(key, value);
        heap.add(node);
        int i = heap.size() - 1;

        while (hasParent(i) && heap.get(i).key < heap.get(parent(i)).key) {
            swap(i, parent(i));
            i = parent(i);
        }
    }

    public Node poll() {
        if (heap.isEmpty()) {
            throw new IllegalStateException("The priority queue is empty.");
        }

        Node minNode = heap.get(0);
        heap.set(0, heap.remove(heap.size() - 1));

        int i = 0;
        while (hasLeft(i)) {
            int minChildIndex = left(i);

            if (hasRight(i) && heap.get(right(i)).key < heap.get(minChildIndex).key) {
                minChildIndex = right(i);
            }

            if (heap.get(i).key < heap.get(minChildIndex).key) {
                break;
            }

            swap(i, minChildIndex);
            i = minChildIndex;
        }

        return minNode;
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return heap.isEmpty();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        PriorityQueue pq = new PriorityQueue();
        pq.offer(3, "C");
        pq.offer(1, "A");
        pq.offer(2, "B");

        while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
            Node node = pq.poll();
            System.out.println(node.key + " " + node.value);
        }
    }
}
```

This code snippet defines a `Node` class for storing key-value pairs and a `PriorityQueue` class that implements a Min-Heap based priority queue. The main methods are `offer` for adding a node to the priority queue and `poll` for removing and returning the node with the highest priority (in this case, the node with the lowest key value).

In the `main` method, a new `PriorityQueue` instance is created, and nodes with different priorities are added using the `offer` method. Finally, the `poll` method is used in a loop to remove and display nodes in the order of their priority.

