Here's an example Java web application using JDBC to retrieve data from a MySQL database and display it on a web page:

1. First, you need to add the MySQL Connector/J driver to your project's classpath. You can download it from the MySQL website and include the JAR file in your project's lib folder.

2. Create a Java servlet class that will handle HTTP requests from the client and fetch data from your MySQL database:

```java
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.PrintWriter;
import java.sql.Connection;
import java.sql.DriverManager;
import java.sql.ResultSet;
import java.sql.Statement;

import javax.servlet.ServletException;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletResponse;

public class DataServlet extends HttpServlet {
    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) throws ServletException, IOException {
        PrintWriter out = response.getWriter();
        try {
            // Load the MySQL Connector/J driver
            Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");

            // Connect to the database
            Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection("jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/your_database_name?useSSL=false&serverTimezone=UTC", "username", "password");

            // Create a statement to execute the SQL query
            Statement stmt = con.createStatement();
            ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT data_field FROM your_table_name");

            // Loop through the result set and output data to the web page
            while (rs.next()) {
                String data = rs.getString("data_field");
                out.println("<p>" + data + "</p>");
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

3. Map this servlet class to a URL pattern in your web.xml file:

```xml
<servlet>
    <servlet-name>DataServlet</servlet-name>
    <servlet-class>DataServlet</servlet-class>
</servlet>

<servlet-mapping>
    <servlet-name>DataServlet</servlet-name>
    <url-pattern>/data</url-pattern>
</servlet-mapping>
```

