The `Driver` object has methods that use the car's well-defined interface to control its speed and direction without accessing its internal state. By isolating the `Driver` object from the `Car` object in this way, you can modify and test each object independently without affecting the other.

Of course, this is just a simplified example of how you can model objects in a loosely-coupled way. In a real-world system, there would likely be many more objects with more complex interfaces, but the principle remains the same: isolate objects from each other using well-defined interfaces.

